metadata.name: Rococo #296
metadata.description:
Manual Dutch Auction (DA): 150 ¬∑ 100 ¬∑ 70 ¬∑ 50 ¬∑ 40 ¬∑ 35 every 8 minutes. Auction will stop changing price when non-reserves are fully minted.

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////

Nature‚Äôs wild flourish and untamed growth wondrously represent the exacting function of beauty ‚Äî a function that is at once useful and infinitely creative. Perhaps nowhere is this delicate symbiosis better observed than in the flower, wherein a pure balance of physical fundamentals exists beneath ornate patterns and elaborate aesthetics.

Amongst the layers of undulating, vividly colored petals, attention-grabbing stigma and stamen, and lusciously decorative features, nature‚Äôs organic abundance and disorder disguises its masterful propensity for precision. Each of the flower‚Äôs components evolve through unpredictable interactions with an unwieldy natural environment, creating spectacular adaptations that emerge from the tension between what attracts.

Rococo painters appreciated the organic fluidity found in flowers and vegetal forms, using their joyful abundance to depict a break from the rigid and stoic period the artists hoped to leave behind. They sought to reframe perfection away from predictability and toward compositions as surprising as the natural world around them.

Thus, ‚ÄòRococo‚Äô is a generative distortion of an old tradition: a digital painting created entirely with code that interprets and processes the natural world‚Äôs dichotomies. This painting algorithm builds upon natural structures while melding and moving their colors beyond form, growing randomly organic iterations that are as perfect as they are imperfect.

Created by Ori Ben-Shabat & Ronen Tanchum @Phenomenalabs
Creative contributions from Tender @tender_art

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////

Technical Details:

- Mobile/GPU Intensive
- Press ‚Äús‚Äù to save a .png of the artwork in live view
- Press ‚Äúp‚Äù to render a high res output + press ‚Äús‚Äù to save a printable .png

metadata.name: Shapes on a Plane #438
metadata.description:
‚ÄúShapes on a Plane‚Äù explores imaginary structures and worlds through simple shapes. It‚Äôs intended for small-scale print.

As a kid I was obsessed with Lego, Duplo, wooden building blocks... anything I could make something with.

I‚Äôd spend hours building things, imagining new worlds, new machines, new concepts, then i‚Äôd take them apart and create a whole new idea to explore.

To me, this piece to me is a reminder of that time - many days spent exploring ideas with those simple objects - no care for viability, for marketability, for audiences or business. Just pure fun.

Without this time in my life, I doubt I‚Äôd have found my passion for creating in the way I do today.

metadata.name: Miniscapes #353
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

metadata.name: dg5721() #53
metadata.description:
A tiny neural network with 5721 neurons, that tries to imitate human handwriting by generating new hallucinated digits in real-time.

It can generate these digits at any resolution and will invent its own ways to fill the gaps.

- Press <SPACE> or click to toggle the infinite latent space exploration.
- Press <S> to save the current frame as PNG at the current screen resolution x2.

It can be installed to work offline (Install button in the URL bar in Chrome or "Add to Home screen" on iOS)

As of 2021, this artwork requires a fast computer or mobile phone.

metadata.name: Espacios comunes #260
metadata.description:
At moment we decide to draw a square on top of a circle, we are defining a time arrow, a third dimension on the 2D plane, where shapes can be on o top of each other, come one after the other. In this project i wanted to remove that time arrow, that third dimension, and leave the 2D plane as flat as possible.

Shapes are not drawn in sequence, they are formed by the continuous addition of points to each region defined by the shapes intersections. Not a single region is on top of the other. They are the result of the combination of shapes, and defined by them. Horizontal, decentralized societies. Espacios comunes. We can see the circles, squares, plane cuts, but we cannot give them an order or authority.

-----

Key controls:

- UP arrow: Increases the sketch resolution. It will take longer to render but it will produce better quality images.
- DOWN arrow: Decreases the sketch resolution.
- f: Removes or adds an empty frame around the image.
- d: Increases the points density. More points will be painted and regions will become more full.
- n: Increases the pixel noise.
- b: Decreases the pixel noise.
- z: Switches on and off the simple pixel sorting algorithm. Move the mouse left and right to change the pixel stickiness.
- x: Switches on and off a more complex version of the pixel sorting algorithm.
- i: Displays some log information.
- p: Pauses the sketch.
- s: Saves a screenshot of the artwork. The image resolution will depend on the sketch resolution, which is controlled by the UP and DOWN arrows.

-----

URL controls:

width=2000 will set the sketch width to 2000 pixels.
proportion=2.3 will set the sketch width-to-height ratio to 2.3.
You can combine these two parameters to create any image output you want. For example, to create an image that is 3000 pixels wide and 5000 pixels high, one just needs to add &width=3000&proportion=0.6 to the URL.

-----

Special thanks to @andregorayeb (Gora) and @ItonkStudio (Itonk) for letting me use some of their color palettes for this project.

-----

This project makes use of the p5.js library. Thank you to all the people that contributed to it.
https://p5js.org

metadata.name: Digital Surrogates #88
metadata.description:
‚ÄúAllan McCollum‚Äôs Plaster Surrogates was a thought-provoking series of sculptures that examines the role of art in contemporary society. The sculptures are cast from plaster and painted to resemble frames, mats, and black rectangles, creating a visual illusion of empty picture frames. McCollum's intention with the surrogates was to comment on the mass production and consumption of art objects, as well as the way in which art is often valued for its social function rather than its inherent aesthetic qualities.‚Äù

Continuing the integration of generative art and conceptual art, this work is a digital reproduction and inspiration of Plaster Surrogates - 1982 by noted conceptual artist, Allan McCollum.

Even though the original work had completely black rectangles, in this work, contrasting colors are used in some variations to increase the beauty. The dimensions and colors of the frames are calculated according to McCollum's original work. Various color palettes and canvas sizes have been used.

-----------

No images are used, created entirely by coding. Textures such as wood, canvas, and oil paint have been created to create a realistic look. Preview optimized for fxhash capturing system and full rendering can take up to several minutes, so I highly recommend checking out this artwork in high quality.


To save the artwork in high resolution, Open it in the live mode, it will be saved automatically after completion.

Made with p5js.
